      <text><![CDATA[Graph Analysis: Hyperbola and Intersecting Lines with B > 0]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>A conic in the two-dimensional plane is the solution set of an equation of the form</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle ax^{2}+bxy+cy^{2}+dx+ey+f=0\)</p>
<p>for real parameters \(\displaystyle a,b,c,d,e\) and \(f,\) where at least one of the \(a,b\) and \(c\) is not zero.</p>
<p>If \(\displaystyle b^{2}-4ac &gt;0\) then the graph is a hyperbola (or two intersecting lines).</p>
<p> Consider the following equation: \(\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F\).</p>
<br>Identify the corresponding values of \(\displaystyle a=\)[[input:ans1]] \(,\displaystyle b=\)[[input:ans2]] \(,c=\) [[input:ans3a]],  \(f=\)[[input:ans3]] [[feedback:prt1]]
<p> [[validation:ans1]] [[validation:ans2]] [[validation:ans3]] [[validation:ans3a]]</p>
<p> So, \(\displaystyle b^{2}−4ac=\)[[input:ans4]] \(,B \neq 0\) [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p>
<p>Therefore, the graph of \(\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F,\) is a hyperbola or two intersecting lines, if \(B \neq 0\). </p>
<p> Case 1: If \(\displaystyle F \neq 0,\)  we have;</p>
<br>\(\displaystyle y=\) [[input:ans5]][[validation:ans5]], thus the graph is a [[input:ans6]][[validation:ans6]][[feedback:prt5]]
<p> Case 2: If \(\displaystyle F = 0\)  we have;</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle x=\)[[input:ans7]][[validation:ans7]] and \(y=\)[[input:ans8]][[validation:ans8]], thus the graph represents [[input:ans10]][[validation:ans10]]  [[feedback:prt6]]</p>

<p>Application:</p>
<p>What is the nature of the graph corresponding to the equation \({@eqn_1@}\)</p>
<p>[[input:ans9]] [[validation:ans9]][[feedback:prt7]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><h3>Worked solution</h3></p>
<p>A conic in the two-dimensional plane is the solution set of an equation of the form</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle ax^{2}+bxy+cy^{2}+dx+ey+f=0\)</p>
<p>for real parameters \(\displaystyle a,b,c,d,e\) and \(f,\) where at least one of the \(a,b\) and \(c\) is not zero.</p>
<p>If \(\displaystyle b^{2}-4ac >0\) then the graph is a hyperbola (or two intersecting lines).</p>
<p> Consider the following equation: \(\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F\).</p>

<p>\(\displaystyle a={@ta_1@},b={@ta_2@},c=0,f={@ta_3@}\)</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle b^{2}−4ac=B^{2}−4(1)(0)={@ta_4@} >0,B \neq 0\).</p>
<p>Therefore, the graph of \(\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F,\) is a hyperbola or two intersecting lines, if \(B \neq 0\). </p>
<p> Case 1: If \(\displaystyle F \neq 0,\)  we have;</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle y={@ta_5@}\), thus the graph is a {@mcq_correct(ta_6)[1]@}.</p>
<p> Case 2: If \(\displaystyle F = 0, x^{2}+Bxy=0,\)  we have; </p>
<p>\(\displaystyle x={@ta_7@}\) and \(y={@ta_8@}\), thus the graph represents {@mcq_correct(ta_10)[1]@}.</p>
<p>As a result, the graph is a hyperbola when \(F\neq 0\) and intersecting lines when \(F=0\).</p>]]></text>
